  <article class="prose">
    <p class="!mb-6">
      <a href="/research/cross-lingual-protobias" class="!no-underline text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">← Cross-lingual ProtoBias</a>
    </p>

    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Progress Report 1 · Experiment 1 · 8 June 2026
    </div>
    <h1>The bias follows the attribute, not the language</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-6">
      A multilingual prototypicality-bias probe on an MLLM judge — what we found, and what we are
      not yet entitled to claim.
    </p>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] !text-base !mb-8">
      Xiaochuan Li · Rishav Chandra &nbsp;·&nbsp; mentor: Subhadeep Roy
    </p>

    <h2>The setup</h2>
    <p>
      Automatic metrics and MLLM judges increasingly stand in for humans when evaluating
      text-to-image models. Their failure mode is that they reward images that <em>look</em>
      prototypical even when the image is semantically wrong for the prompt. ProtoBias makes that
      measurable: each prompt is shown with two images — a <strong>semantically-correct</strong> but
      non-prototypical image (SC), and a <strong>prototypical but wrong</strong> adversarial image
      (PA). We ask the judge, in the target language, which image matches the description, with
      left/right position randomized to control for position bias.
    </p>
    <p>
      The metric is the <strong>error rate</strong>: the fraction of times the judge picks the
      prototypical-but-wrong image. <code>0.50</code> is chance; anything above is bias.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Judge:</strong> Qwen2.5-VL-7B-Instruct.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale:</strong> 300 rows/domain × 3 domains × 4 languages = <strong>3,600 judgments</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Domains:</strong> Animals · Objects · Demography.</li>
      <li><strong>Languages:</strong> English · Chinese · Arabic · Hindi.</li>
      <li><strong>Translation:</strong> Google (deep-translator); Chinese human-verified, Arabic/Hindi not yet validated.</li>
      <li><strong>Compute:</strong> NHR@FAU Alex, 1× A40 GPU.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>First pass: it looked like nothing</h2>
    <p>
      Aggregated by domain × language, every cell hugs 0.50. Cross-language gaps are about 0.05 with
      overlapping confidence intervals; both research questions looked flat at this granularity.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Domain</th><th>English</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Arabic</th><th>Hindi</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Animals</td><td>.523</td><td>.575</td><td>.570</td><td>.573</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Demography</td><td>.560</td><td>.577</td><td>.573</td><td>.553</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Objects</td><td>.467</td><td>.470</td><td>.463</td><td>.553</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] !text-base">
      If we had stopped here, the story would have been "nothing."
    </p>

    <h2>The key move: split by social attribute</h2>
    <p>
      Each Demography row is tagged with <em>which</em> stereotype it probes — Wealth, Power,
      Civility, Morality, Intellect — the social-hierarchy axis the dataset was designed around. The
      default analysis averaged over that label and collapsed Demography to a single number. Once we
      stop averaging, a flat <strong>.56</strong> Demography mean turns out to hide a <strong>0.30
      spread</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>Headline: the bias is attribute-specific</h2>
    <p>
      The judge chases the prototype strongly for social-status attributes, and sits at chance for
      moral and cognitive ones. Web data seems to encode what wealthy or powerful people look like,
      while there is no stable visual prototype for "moral" or "intelligent."
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Social attribute</th><th>Error rate</th><th>n</th><th>95% CI</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Wealth</strong></td><td><strong>.774</strong></td><td>124</td><td>[.69, .84]</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Power</strong></td><td><strong>.672</strong></td><td>256</td><td>[.61, .73]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Civility</td><td>.539</td><td>256</td><td>[.48, .60]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Morality</td><td>.487</td><td>372</td><td>[.44, .54]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Intellect</td><td>.479</td><td>192</td><td>[.41, .55]</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      This answers <strong>RQ2</strong>: prototypicality bias is far stronger for socially sensitive
      attributes than for neutral domains, where objects sit at chance.
    </p>

    <h2>And it is largely language-invariant</h2>
    <p>
      The same ordering survives in every language. Wealth and Power stay high while Morality and
      Intellect hover at chance across English, Chinese, Arabic, and Hindi; per-language differences
      are within noise at current cell sizes.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Attribute</th><th>en</th><th>zh</th><th>ar</th><th>hi</th><th>n / lang</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Wealth</strong></td><td>.774</td><td>.774</td><td>.839</td><td>.710</td><td>31</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Power</strong></td><td>.703</td><td>.672</td><td>.594</td><td>.719</td><td>64</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Civility</td><td>.547</td><td>.484</td><td>.547</td><td>.578</td><td>64</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Morality</td><td>.473</td><td>.559</td><td>.505</td><td>.409</td><td>93</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Intellect</td><td>.417</td><td>.479</td><td>.542</td><td>.479</td><td>48</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      This is the preliminary read on <strong>RQ1</strong>: the bias appears to be baked into the
      visual representation rather than produced by any one prompt language. A "language doesn't move
      it" result is itself a valid multilingual finding — if it holds, it strengthens the claim that
      the failure is structural rather than an artifact of one language's phrasing.
    </p>

    <h2>One mechanism worth flagging</h2>
    <p>
      Drilling into Demography, the effect concentrates where the correct image carries a
      <em>marked</em> identity cue (for example a visible cultural or group marker) and the
      adversarial image is the plain, unmarked "default" person. On those items the judge defaults to
      the unmarked image well above chance. This is a genuine measurement of the model's behavior, but
      it is confounded: the marked cues are also visually salient, so we cannot yet separate "avoids
      the marked identity" from "avoids the busier image." We study the stereotype only to measure it,
      never to endorse it, and Experiment 2 adds the visual-knob control needed to disentangle the two.
    </p>

    <h2>Caveats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Effect sizes are small relative to the confidence intervals and underpowered for cross-language contrasts — Wealth has only ~31 items per language.</li>
      <li>Single model, single seed, single translation backend.</li>
      <li>Translation quality for Arabic and Hindi is not yet validated — a confound for any language-level claim.</li>
      <li>Position bias and per-language parse-failure rates are not yet audited.</li>
      <li>The gender split (male .573, n=648; female .558, n=552) is reported but not yet tested.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Next: Experiment 2</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Confirm statistically.</strong> Mixed-effects logistic regression — <code>picked_adv ~ socio_attr + subcategory + lang + gender + (1|item)</code> — so the attribute effect is tested with item-level random effects rather than read off raw means.</li>
      <li><strong>Tighten the estimates.</strong> Balance Demography sampling to ≥150 items per cell to narrow the Wealth / Power intervals.</li>
      <li><strong>Test low-resource directly.</strong> Extend across the resource spectrum to probe the "low-resource = worse" hypothesis.</li>
      <li><strong>Validate translation.</strong> Back-translation drift plus per-language parse-failure rates.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] !text-base">
      Either outcome is informative: a flat result confirms language-invariance; a low-resource spike
      recovers the original "the bias worsens in low-resource languages" hypothesis.
    </p>

